LINUX LOGGING 

⸻

1. LOGGING ARCHITECTURE OVERVIEW

Linux logging is multi-layered, not a single system:

Layer	Tool	Purpose
Kernel	dmesg, kern.log	Hardware + core system
System	syslog, rsyslog	General logging pipeline
Journal	journalctl	Structured systemd logs
Security	auditd	Fine-grained monitoring
Auth	auth.log	Access + privilege
Application	Apache logs	Entry point (attacks)


⸻

2. KERNEL LOGGING (DEEP LEVEL)

Sources
	•	/var/log/kern.log
	•	dmesg (ring buffer)

Characteristics
	•	Volatile (ring buffer overwritten)
	•	Persistent copy via rsyslog

⸻

Advanced Commands

Filter by keyword

dmesg | grep -i "error"

Human-readable timestamps

dmesg -T

Live monitoring

dmesg -w


⸻

Example + Deep Analysis

custom_kernel: loading out-of-tree module taints kernel

	•	out-of-tree → not official
	•	taints → disables trust model

→ Kernel integrity broken

⸻

3. SYSLOG / RSYSLOG (PIPELINE CONTROL)

Config Files

/etc/rsyslog.conf
/etc/rsyslog.d/*.conf


⸻

Example Rule

auth,authpriv.*   /var/log/auth.log
kern.*            /var/log/kern.log
*.*;auth.none     /var/log/syslog

Meaning
	•	Facility + severity routing
	•	Controls where logs go

⸻

Advanced Concepts

Facility + Severity

facility.level

Example:

auth.warning
kern.err


⸻

Log Forwarding (SIEM)

*.* @@192.168.1.100:514

	•	@@ → TCP forwarding
	•	Sends logs to central server

⸻

4. JOURNALCTL (STRUCTURED ANALYSIS)

Key Strength
	•	Indexed logs
	•	Fast filtering
	•	Combines all sources

⸻

Core Parameters (IMPORTANT)

Time Filtering

journalctl -S "2024-06-01" -U "2024-06-02"

Relative Time

journalctl -S "1 hour ago"


⸻

Boot Analysis

journalctl -b        # current boot
journalctl -b -1     # previous boot


⸻

Service Filtering

journalctl -u ssh.service


⸻

Priority Filtering

journalctl -p err
journalctl -p crit


⸻

Kernel Logs Only

journalctl -k


⸻

Output Control

journalctl -n 50
journalctl -r
journalctl --no-pager


⸻

Example + Analysis

sudo[77794]: auth could not identify password for [www-data]

→ Web service attempting privilege escalation

⸻

Storage Modes

/etc/systemd/journald.conf

Options:
	•	Storage=volatile → RAM only
	•	Storage=persistent → disk

⸻

5. AUDITD (FORENSIC-GRADE LOGGING)

Components
	•	auditd → daemon
	•	auditctl → rule creation
	•	ausearch → query
	•	aureport → summary

⸻

Rule Types

File Monitoring

auditctl -w /etc/passwd -p wra -k users

Syscall Monitoring

auditctl -a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S execve -k exec


⸻

Parameter Breakdown

auditctl

Flag	Meaning
-w	watch file
-p	permissions (r,w,x,a)
-k	key/tag
-a	action
-F	filter
-S	syscall


⸻

ausearch (IMPORTANT)

Search by key

ausearch -k users

Human-readable output

ausearch -i -k users

Filter by time

ausearch -ts today
ausearch -ts 10:00 -te 12:00

Filter by user

ausearch -ua 1000

Filter by command

ausearch -x bash


⸻

Example Event

type=SYSCALL comm="vim" exe="/usr/bin/vim"
type=PATH name="/var/www/html/cmd.php"

Interpretation
	•	File accessed → web shell
	•	Tool used → vim

⸻

aureport

Summary Reports

aureport -x   # commands executed
aureport -u   # users
aureport -f   # files


